  1. Plot the time series of sales of product A. Can you identify seasonal fluctuations and/or a trend?
plot(plastics)

Temos uma trend que est aumentando conforme os anos e uma sazonalidade anual.

  1. Use an STL decomposition to calculate the trend-cycle and seasonal indices. (Experiment with having fixed or changing seasonality.)
plastics.fit <- stl(plastics, s.window="periodic")
plot(plastics.fit)

plastics.fit <- stl(plastics, s.window=5)
plot(plastics.fit)

plastics.fit <- stl(plastics, s.window=7)
plot(plastics.fit)

Restos e trend sofreram grandes alteraes, mas qual o melhor?

  1. Do the results support the graphical interpretation from part (a)?

Sim!

  1. Compute and plot the seasonally adjusted data
plastics.fit.adj <- seasadj(plastics.fit)
plot(plastics.fit.adj)

  1. Change one observation to be an outlier (e.g., add 500 to one observation), and recompute the seasonally adjusted data. What is the effect of the outlier
plastics2 <- plastics
plastics2[20] <- plastics2[10] + 500
plastics2.fit <- stl(plastics2, s.window="periodic")
plastics2.fit.adj <- seasadj(plastics2.fit)
plot(plastics2.fit.adj)

  1. Does the outlier have an effect if you use robust=TRUE with the stl function?
plastics3 <- plastics
plastics3[20] <- plastics3[10] + 500
plastics3.fit <- stl(plastics3, s.window="periodic", robust=TRUE)
plastics3.fit.adj <- seasadj(plastics3.fit)
plot(plastics3.fit.adj)
